# Hololand Cursor Rules

You are working in the Hololand codebase - a VR/AR platform with the HoloScript language.

## HoloScript File Types

### .holo files (Visual Flow Language)
- Think of these as **visual graphs**, not code
- Nodes = objects (orbs, buildings, NPCs)
- Edges = connections (events, actions)
- Flow = how data/control moves

When reading .holo, mentally visualize:
```
[Object A] ──event──→ [Object B]
     ↓                    ↓
   state              state
```

### .hsplus files (Full Language)
- Use for complex logic, backends, systems
- Has variables, functions, loops, async/await

## Generating .holo

When asked to create scenes/worlds, output .holo with this structure:

```holo
composition "Name" {
  // 1. Templates define node types
  template "TypeName" {
    state { }
    action name() { }
  }

  // 2. Spatial groups organize nodes
  spatial_group "GroupName" {
    object "Instance" using "TypeName" {
      position: [x, y, z]
    }
  }

  // 3. Logic defines flow
  logic {
    on_event { }
    every(ms) { }
  }
}
```

## Common Patterns

NPC: `object "Name" { traits: ["talkable"] }`
Interactive: `orb "Name" { interactive: true, on_interact { } }`
Collectible: `traits: ["collectible", "pulse"]`
Periodic: `every(5000) { action() }`

## Project Structure

- `/packages/core` - Parser, validator, runtime
- `/packages/holoscript-*` - Standard library packages
- `/packages/mcp-server` - MCP tools for agents
- `/packages/brittney-service` - Local AI assistant
- `/examples/` - Example worlds

## Key Principle

.holo is designed for AI agents to read/write. Keep it declarative and visual. Use .hsplus when you need real programming.
